'''Gerald B. Gainous''' was a resident of Washington D.C. who climbed the fence surrounding the [[White House]] four times in 1975 and 1976 during the [[Gerald Ford|Ford]] administration.<ref>{{Cite news|work=Reading Eagle |date=August 16, 1976 |page=6 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bMQhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=j6AFAAAAIBAJ&dq=gerald%20gainous&pg=5255%2C2051015 |access-date=August 7, 2011 |title=Young Man Again Caught Scaling White House Fence}}</ref> 

In the first incident, which occurred November 26, 1975, he was able to walk about the grounds without being stopped for about 90 minutes.<ref>[[Federation of American Scientists]], [http://www.fas.org/irp/agency/ustreas/usss/t1pubrpt.html White House Security Review]</ref> He approached the President's daughter, [[Susan Ford]], as she was unloading camera equipment from her car, before carrying on.<ref>[http://prop1.org/park/pave/rev9.htm Protection of the White House Complex in the Twentieth Century]</ref> He was freed on probation after that incident.

Gainous claimed he was trying to gain the President's attention in order to obtain a pardon for his father who had been convicted of conspiring to import heroin.<ref>{{Cite news|work=Calgary Herald |date=August 16, 1976 |page=8 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eYxkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AoANAAAAIBAJ&pg=5853%2C2539545 |access-date=August 7, 2011 |title=White House fence stunt repeated: Intruder getting familiar}}</ref>

