[[File:Kakwa people Uganda DRC South Sudan.png|thumb|The geographic distribution of the Kakwa people (approx.).]]

The '''Kakwa people''' are found in north-western [[Uganda]], south-western [[South Sudan]], and north-eastern [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], particularly to the west of the [[White Nile]] river.<ref name="Gateseoa629">{{cite book | author1=Anthony Appiah | author2=Henry Louis Gates | title=Encyclopedia of Africa | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A0XNvklcqbwC | year=2010 | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=978-0-19-533770-9 | page=629}}</ref>

==Demography== 
The Kakwa people are a small minority but a part of the larger [[Bari people|Karo people]], an intermarried group that also includes the [[Bari people|Bari]], [[Pojulu people|Pojulu]], [[Mundari people|Mundari]], [[Kuku people|Kuku]] and [[Nyangwara]]. Their language, [[Kutuk language|Kutuk na Kakwa]], is an [[Eastern Nilotic languages|Eastern Nilotic]] language.<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=keo Kakwa languages], Ethnologue</ref>

The major cities of the Kakwa people are the [[Yei, South Sudan|Yei]] and [[Morobo]] districts (South Sudan), [[Koboko district]] (Uganda), [[Imgbokolo]] and [[Aba, Democratic Republic of the Congo]]. The Kakwa people sometimes refer to themselves as "Kakwa Saliya Musala", translated directly as "kakwa three hills" a phrase they commonly use to denote their 'oneness' in spite of being politically dispersed among three countries.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}

==History==
According to the Kakwa [[oral tradition]], they migrated out of East Africa (Nubian region) from the city of [[Kawa (Sudan)|Kawa]] in between the [[Cataracts of the Nile|third and fourth cataracts of the Nile]]. First into South Sudan, and from there southwards into Uganda and the Democratic Republic of the Congo.<ref name="Gateseoa629"/> The Kakwa converted to Islam, accepting the Maliki school of Sunni theology in medieval era. They were annexed into Equitoria region claimed by the Egyptian Islamic ruler [[Khedive Ismail]] (Isma'il Pasha) by his descendant Tewfik Pasha in 1889. As the British colonial empire expanded into East Africa and Egypt, the region with Kakwa people became a part of the [[Uganda Protectorate]].<ref name="Gateseoa629"/>

[[File:Idi Amin -Archives New Zealand AAWV 23583, KIRK1, 5(B), R23930288.jpg|thumb|140px|left|General [[Idi Amin]] was born in Kakwa ethnic group.]]

The Kakwa people rose to international prominence when one of their descendant General [[Idi Amin]] assumed the power in Uganda through a coup.<ref name="Otiso2006p31">{{cite book|author=Kefa M. Otiso|title=Culture and Customs of Uganda|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rMnkcZsv_eEC&pg=PA31|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood |isbn=978-0-313-33148-0|pages=31–33}}</ref> He filled important military and civil positions in his administration with his ethnic group,<ref name="Otiso2006p31"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Thabani ka Sigogo Sibanda|title=Conflict Issues Across Disciplines: Conflict, Negotiation, and Mediation: African Experiences|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XPiDm4o-lbIC&pg=PA67|year=2011|publisher=Xlibris|isbn=978-1-4568-1761-9|pages=67–68}}</ref>{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=December 2017}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Phares Mukasa Mutibwa|title=Uganda Since Independence: A Story of Unfulfilled Hopes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EkSP9XUIAKsC |year=1992|publisher=Africa World Press|isbn=978-0-86543-357-1|pages=79–81}}</ref> and [[Nubians]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Donald L. Horowitz|title=Ethnic Groups in Conflict, Updated Edition With a New Preface|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1nC8htP6SE4C |year=2001|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-92631-8|pages=491–492}}</ref> He arrested and killed officials from other ethnic groups such as the Acholi and Lango people, whom he doubted.<ref name="Gateseoa629"/> Idi Amin also supplied arms and financed the Sudanese Kakwa people in the first civil war of Sudan.<ref>{{cite book|author=Donald L. Horowitz|title=Ethnic Groups in Conflict, Updated Edition With a New Preface|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1nC8htP6SE4C |year=2001|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-92631-8|pages=274–281}}</ref> The Kakwa officials in Idi Amin regime were later accused of many humanitarian crimes. After Amin was deposed in 1979, many Kakwa people were killed in revenge killings, causing others to leave the area and fled to Sudan.<ref name="Gateseoa629"/> However, they have now returned to their native areas in the West Nile region of northern Uganda.<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/place/Uganda/The-Republic-of-Uganda#ref419313 The Republic of Uganda], Encyclopædia Britannica</ref>

===Ethnic violence===
{{See also|Ethnic violence in South Sudan#Equatorians-Dinka_fighting|l1=Equatorians-Dinka fighting}}
For most of the [[South Sudanese Civil War]], the fighting was focused in the [[Greater Upper Nile]] region. After the clashes in Juba in 2016, the fighting largely shifted to the previously safe haven of [[Equatoria]], where the bulk of SPLM-IO forces went for shelter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irinnews.org/analysis/2016/11/14/who-can-stop-threat-genocide-south-sudan|title=Who can stop the threat of genocide in South Sudan?|date=14 November 2016|publisher=irinnews.org}}</ref> Accounts point to both sides targeting civilians on ethnic lines between the Dinka and the dozens of ethnic groups among the Equatorians who are historically in conflict with the Dinka, such as the Karo, who include the [[Bari people|Bari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southsudan-congo-refugees-idUSKBN13Q50M|title=South Sudanese flee as country edges closer to 'genocide'|date=1 December 2016|publisher=reuters}}</ref> Witnesses report Dinka soldiers threatening villagers that they will kill all Kakwa people for their alleged support to Machar and killing [[Pojulu people]] while sparing those who they find can speak [[Dinka language|Dinka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/us-seeks-sanctions-on-south-sudan-rebel-leader-army-chief/2016/11/18/95a75fd4-ae11-11e6-8f19-21a1c65d2043_story.html|title=US seeks sanctions on South Sudan rebel leader, army chief|date=19 November 2016|publisher=washington post}}</ref> A UN investigation said rape was being used a tool of ethnic cleansing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/united-nations-says-rape-used-as-tool-for-ethnic-cleansing-in-south-sudan/|title=UN:Rape used as a tool of ethnic cleansing in South Sudan|date=2 December 2016|publisher=CBS news}}</ref> and [[Adama Dieng]], the U.N.'s Special Adviser on the Prevention of Genocide, warned of [[genocide]] after visiting areas of fighting in [[Yei River State|Yei]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southsudan-uganda-refugees-idUSKBN1441QU|title=Hatred spills beyond South Sudan along with refugees|date=15 December 2016|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>

==Lifestyle==
The traditional Kakwa livelihood has been based on cultivating [[maize|corn]], [[millet]], [[cassava]], fishing and cattle. The traditional villages of Kakwa are linked by their lineage, with male forming councils of elders. Polygyny is accepted, and the Islamic traditions are a part of the Kakwa people lives.<ref name="Gateseoa629"/>

