{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox scholar | name = Taha Yasseri | image = Taha Yasseri.jpg | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | fullname = | othernames = | birth_name = Taha Yasseri | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1984|09|06}} | birth_place = [[Tehran]], Iran | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | death_cause = | nationality = [[Iran]]ian | residence = [[Oxford]],United Kingdom | era = | region = | workplaces = | alma_mater = [[University of Göttingen]] | thesis_title = Nanoscale pattern formation on ion-sputtered surfaces | thesis_url = https://ediss.uni-goettingen.de/handle/11858/00-1735-0000-0006-B4B9-A?locale-attribute=de | thesis_year = 2010 | doctoral_advisor = Reiner Kree | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | school_tradition = | main_interests = [[Computational social science]] | principal_ideas = | major_works = | awards = W.J.M. Mackenzie Book Prize, for best book published in political science with [[Helen Margetts]], Peter John, and Scott Hale. | influences = | influenced = | website = https://www.oii.ox.ac.uk/people/taha-yasseri/ | footnotes = }}
'''Taha Yasseri''' (born 6 September 1984) is an Iranian [[physicist]] known for his research on Wikipedia and [[computational social science]]. He is a Senior Research Fellow in [[computational social science]] at the [[Oxford Internet Institute]], [[University of Oxford]], a Turing Fellow at [[Alan Turing Institute|the Alan Turing Institute]] for Data Science, and a Research Fellow in Humanities and Social Sciences at [[Wolfson College, Oxford|Wolfson College]], [[University of Oxford]]. Yasseri's research has been widely covered in the media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/xywe54/these-computer-scientists-are-making-a-global-map-of-sexism|title=These Computer Scientists Are Making a ‘Global Map of Sexism’|date=9 October 2015|work=Motherboard|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/feb/23/wikipedia-bot-editing-war-study|title=Study reveals bot-on-bot editing wars raging on Wikipedia's pages|last=Sample|first=Ian|date=23 February 2017|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2016/10/we-care-when-airplane-crashes-and-then-we-don-t|title=We care when an airplane crashes. And then we don't|date=11 October 2016|work=Science {{!}} AAAS|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/nz7dv7/research-confirms-dating-apps-tinder-grindr-happn-bumble-are-a-sad-game | title=Research Confirms Dating Apps Are a Sad Game | first=Jordan | last=Pearson | date=15 July 2016 | work=Vice | accessdate=1 June 2018 }}</ref><ref>https://www.livescience.com/58556-how-long-airplane-crash-memories-last.html</ref>
== Research== ===Wikipedia=== Yasseri has studied the statistical trends of systemic bias at Wikipedia introduced by editing conflicts and their resolution. His research examined the [[counterproductive work behavior]] of edit warring. Yasseri contended that simple reverts or "undo" operations were not the most significant measure of counterproductive behavior at Wikipedia and relied instead on the statistical measurement of detecting "reverting/reverted pairs" or "mutually reverting edit pairs". Such a "mutually reverting edit pair" is defined where one editor reverts the edit of another editor who then, in sequence, returns to revert the first editor in the "mutually reverting edit pairs". The results were tabulated for several language versions of Wikipedia. The English Wikipedia's three largest conflict rates belonged to the articles ''[[George W. Bush]]'', ''[[Anarchism]]'' and ''[[Muhammad]]''. By comparison, for the German Wikipedia, the three largest conflict rates at the time of the [[Oxford]] study were for the articles covering (i) ''[[Croatia]]'', (ii) ''[[Scientology]]'' and (iii) ''[[9/11 conspiracy theories]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yasseri|first=Taha|last2=Spoerri|first2=Anselm|last3=Graham|first3=Mark|last4=Kertesz|first4=Janos|date=23 May 2013|title=The Most Controversial Topics in Wikipedia: A Multilingual and Geographical Analysis|url=https://papers.ssrn.com/abstract=2269392|language=en|location=Rochester, NY}}</ref>
In a study published by ''[[PLoS ONE]]'' in 2012 he estimated the share of contributions to different editions of Wikipedia from different regions of the world. It reported that the proportion of the edits made from North America was 51% for the [[English Wikipedia]], and 25% for the [[simple English Wikipedia]]. The Wikimedia Foundation hopes to increase the number of editors in the Global South to 37% by 2015.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yasseri|first=Taha|last2=Sumi|first2=Robert|last3=Kertész|first3=János|date=17 January 2012|title=Circadian Patterns of Wikipedia Editorial Activity: A Demographic Analysis|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0030091|journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=e30091|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0030091|issn=1932-6203}}</ref>
===Social media and politics=== Yasseri has studied the role of [[social media]] in politics. He has used Wikipedia page view statistics and Google search volumes to understand and potentially predict electoral popularity in different countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/02/election-polling-trouble-can-internet-data-save-it|title=Election polling is in trouble. Can internet data save it?|last= Bohannon|first=John|date=2 February 2017|website=Science|language=en|access-date=2018-05-18}}</ref> He has co-written ''Political Turbulence; How Social Media Shape Collective Action''<ref>https://www.timeshighereducation.com/books/review-political-turbulence-helen-margetts-peter-john-scott-hale-taha-yasseri-princeton-university-press</ref> which was selected among the best politics books of 2016 by [[The Guardian]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/dec/01/best-politics-books-2016-gaby-hinsliff|title=The best politics books of 2016 |last=Hinsliff|first=Gaby|date=1 November 2016|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-05-18}}</ref> and was awarded the [[Political Studies Association]] Book of the year award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oii.ox.ac.uk/news/releases/political-turbulence-how-social-media-shape-collective-action-awarded-book-prize-at-annual-awards-in-westminster/|title=Political Turbulence: How Social Media Shape Collective Action awarded the Political Studies Association book prize|last=OII|first=|date=5 December 2017|website=Oxford Internet Institute|language=en|access-date=2018-05-18}}</ref>
